	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />It is true ppMCK is meant for making .NSF and is not meant to make a game. But I think ppMCK can be compile on Linux it is a C code and is probably portable, although I have not tried it yet (try going into that directory and typing <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">make</tt> and see if it compiles without errors). I have made some improvement of ppMCK, but have not tried it since I have this new computer (with Linux). I do not use syntax colours.<br /><br />It is possible that many people will not want to use ca65 and will prefer ASM6; or in my case, I prefer NESASM.<br /><br />I have also once made a music engine for a Famicom game and used Csound and CsoundMML, but that don't work so well. There is AmigaMML to make music output to .MOD/.XM formats, but that isn't actually suitable for NES/Famicom anyways. (But, possibly a program can be based on modified version of such things, to do something else.)

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


